<p>Madeleine Waters</p><p><strong>The Failed Dragon</strong></p><p>What can you do with a princess no one else wants?</p><p>	Bargtn hadn’t known there were princesses that no one was interested in questing for or paying a ransom to rescue.  Just his luck, to get stuck with the seventh daughter of a penniless king.  How was he supposed to show off his valor and success now?  His mother had always been careful about reminding him how a dragon’s hoard reflected his character—treasure from placating bribes and gifts are testaments to a dragon’s fearsomeness.  A few singed coats of armor hung in an entrance hall will always look impressive to visitors.  </p><p>	Princesses are a different matter.  They’re annoying and hard to feed, and in and of themselves, have very little redeeming value.</p><p>	“You can’t even hunt for yourself,” he grumbled at his captive after the third week without any sign she would be leaving his company.  He still couldn’t believe humans actually had to eat every day.</p><p>	“If I could, I’d certainly pick prey that was more edible than <em>this</em>.”</p><p>	Bargtn wasn’t sure if he should be thankful that at least she wasn’t boring or peeved that her responses were so bratty.  He huffed in frustration, allowing small spurts of flame to rise in his nostrils.  The girl didn’t even flinch as she had when he’d first taken her; she just picked at a gash in the sleeve of her gown and stared disdainfully at the charred ox he’d brought for her dinner.  <em>I am a failure</em>.</p><p>	He flopped down on the cave floor; the princess’s disgruntlement was audible as she jumped to avoid his tail.</p><p>	“You’re pathetic,” she said.</p><p>	“What would you expect of a dragon who can’t even properly ransom a princess?”  He did not bury his face in his paws soon enough to miss her eyes roll.</p><p>	“You could try to actually solve your problem instead of simply whining about it.”</p><p>	“How do you mean ‘try to solve it’?  It’s not <em>my</em> fault no one wants you.”</p><p>	The princess did flinch a little at that, becoming somehow smaller.  Were he not trapped in throes of self-pity, the dragon would have been intrigued by the effect; the princess had always seemed large by human standards.</p><p>	Her voice remained as sharp as ever.  “It’s your fault you clearly haven’t the faintest idea what you’re doing.”</p><p>	“Well—it’s not as if there’s some grand master protocol written down somewhere for me to follow.”  When this excellent point provoked no reaction, Bargtn demanded, “How would you do it then?”</p><p>	“An obvious place to start is good location.  This cave is inconspicuous and hard to find—you want some nice abandoned castle or a tower in the woods.  Burn down some trees in the area or something to let the locals know you’re there and you mean business.  Would be rescuers are much more likely to take on quests with clear destinations.”</p><p>	Bargtn blinked.  He hadn’t expected her to have any sort of answer prepared, and condescension aside, well.  He was beginning to see exactly why she kept besting him at riddles.</p><p>	“I like solving problems,” she said.</p><p>	“Well—go on,” Bargtn prompted when she failed to say anything more.  In the moment before she complied her eyes flicked to his; Bargtn had the sense she was sizing him up.</p><p>	“Your hospitality needs a lot of work.  Knights are out to rescue <em>beautiful</em> princesses, not—“ she faltered “—ugly ones, unwashed without makeup or brushed hair.”</p><p>	“What’s the point?” Surely the princesses could just be washed after they were rescued.</p><p>	“The point is <em>comfort</em>.”  The princess gestured with increasing enthusiasm, splitting the seam of her dress sleeve even further.  “That means proper food, a comfortable place to sleep, a stream or tub to wash in—“</p><p>	“Garments to replace any that I rip?”</p><p>	“Yes, exactly!”  The princess pulled up the corners of her mouth to bare her teeth; Bargtn nearly snarled at her before he remembered this was how humans exhibited pleasure.  “It probably wouldn’t go amiss to have some books or things as well.”</p><p>	“Why?”</p><p>	“Courtesy, I suppose.  A princess who’s obviously been cared for nicely is far less likely to be justification for a dragon hunting party.”</p><p>	Bargtn swished his tail uncomfortably.  A large enough group was perfectly capable of taking down a dragon with arrows; their wings weren’t armored.  Far better to get would-be champions who would fight one on one.</p><p>	“Speaking of which,” the princess forged ahead, “your manners leave quite a bit to be desired.”</p><p>	Bargnt couldn’t help his snort.  “I’m a <em>dragon</em>.”</p><p>	“Well, and you’re a very rude one.  You’ve never even asked my name.”  She put her hands on her hips, and curls bounced over her shoulders.  Bargtn sighed—no one should be able to be that openly insolent to a dragon.  He decided not to flame her though—her ideas really hadn’t been bad.</p><p>	“What’s your name, then?”</p><p>	“Alyssa.  And yours?”</p><p>	“Bartn.”</p><p>	“Nice to meet you, Brarck.”</p><p>	“It’s Bargtn,” he corrected her.  Clumsy human tongues couldn’t pronounce anything right.</p><p>	“I don’t think that’s a sound I’m actually capable of making.  I’ll just call you Bar.”</p><p>	Bargnt glowered at this indignity, but his pride had grown wings and flown quite away at least a week ago, so he said nothing.</p><p>	“Now let’s practice,” Alyssa continued.  “Bar, I’m hungry.  Could you please fetch some food?  <em>Human</em> food?”</p><p>	“Alright,” he agreed.  “I’ll go and get us dinner.  You stay here and work on a plan.”</p><p>	“A plan for what?”</p><p>	Bargtn cocked his head—she may have been annoying, but he’d never thought her stupid.</p><p>	“A plan to capture a princess and successfully ransom her off,” he said slowly, as though speaking to a hatchling.  Humans, honestly.  They’d only been discussing the matter for the last twenty minutes.</p><p>	“Now wait, I never said I would <em>help</em> you.” </p><p>	Bargtn wondered at his evaluation of her intelligence.  Then again, perhaps she was just acting; humans were famous for refusing to do something if they got nothing in return.  She was probably trying to strike a bargain.</p><p>	Well, he could offer her an excellent deal.  “Help me kidnap another princess and <em>successfully</em> collect a ransom for her, and I’ll take you back home.”</p><p>	Alyssa inhaled sharply.  As Bargtn watched, her teeth started to worry at her bottom lip, but his gaze soon wandered away to determine the most appropriate corner of the cave in which to store his hoard.</p><p>	“You have to promise not to kill anyone in the process and not to hurt me or the other princess in any way.”</p><p>	Bargtn looked back and waved a claw dismissively.  “Done.”</p><p>	“In that case, get some parchment and a quill while you’re out.  I like to write my ideas down.”</p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
